Provide a visual overview of the top 10 most common types of violations (feel free to group them into categories if reasonable). Compare how this ranking differs if we focus on the total amount of revenue generated.

Top 5 are the same, from ranking 6 to 10, the rankings are different because of different fine amount.

data_top10 <- df %>% group_by(Violation.Code)%>% 
dplyr::summarise(count = n()) %>%
    top_n(10)
## Selecting by count
data_top10 <-left_join(data_top10,vio_code_1, by = c ("Violation.Code"= "Violation.Code"))

data_top10_rev <- df %>% filter(!is.na(fine)) %>% group_by(Violation.Code)%>% 
  summarise_at(vars(fine),list(total= sum)) %>%
    top_n(10)
## Selecting by total
data_top10_rev <-left_join(data_top10_rev,vio_code_1, by = c ("Violation.Code"= "Violation.Code"))
ggplot(data_top10, aes(x = Violation.Description, y = count)) + 
  geom_bar(color = "black", stat = "identity", aes(fill= count))+ 
  coord_flip()

ggplot( data_top10_rev, aes(x = Violation.Description, y = total)) + 
  geom_bar(color = "black", stat = "identity", aes( fill= total))+ 
  coord_flip()

  1. Effect of COVID Lets see if we can observe the effect of COVID restrictions on parking violations. Present a visualization that shows how parking violations changed after the New York statewide stay-at-home order on March 14, 2020. Make sure the visualization clearly highlights the main pattern (the COVID effect).
data_covid <- df %>% group_by(Issue.Date) %>% dplyr::summarise(count=n())
data_covid$Date <-as.Date(data_covid$Issue.Date,"%m/%d/%Y")

highlight_max <- data_covid %>%  
filter(Date > "2020-03-14" & Date <"2020-06-14")

ggplot(data = data_covid, aes(x = Date, y = count))+
  geom_line()+
  geom_point(data=highlight_max, aes(x = Date, y = count), color='red',size=3)+ theme(legend.position = "none")

m <- leaflet(loca_geo) %>%
  addTiles() %>%    
  addCircles(lng = ~lon, lat = ~lat)

                 "Issue Date",loca_geo$Issue.Date,"<br/>",
                 "Registration State",loca_geo$Registration.State,"<br/>")
(mpop2 <- m %>% addCircles( popup = content))

  1. Luxury cars and repeat offenders Using the vehicle Plate ID, identify repeat offenders (in the full dataset). Create another variable called luxury_car in which you identify luxury car brands using the Vehicle Make variable.

Start with the previous map. Distinguish the points by whether the car is a repeat offender and/or luxury car. Add a legend informing the user about the color scheme. Also make sure that the added information about the car type and repeat offender status is now contained in the popup information. Show this map.

df_count <- df %>% group_by(Plate.ID) %>% dplyr::summarise(count=n())
loca_geo  <- left_join(loca_geo , df_count, by = c ("Plate.ID"= "Plate.ID"))
loca_geo1 <-loca_geo %>%  mutate(luxury_car = case_when(Vehicle.Make == "ROVER" ~ "luxury", 
                                                        Vehicle.Make == "BMW" ~ "luxury",
                                Vehicle.Make == "LEXUS" ~ "luxury"))%>%
  mutate(lux_repeat= case_when(luxury_car == "luxury" ~ "1"))%>%  
  mutate(lux_repeat = ifelse(count >1, 1,0))

m2 <- leaflet(loca_geo1) %>%
  addTiles() %>%    
  addCircles(lng = ~lon, lat = ~lat)

factpal <- colorFactor(topo.colors(2), loca_geo1$lux_repeat)

content <- paste("ID",loca_geo1$Plate.ID,"<br/>",
                 "Issue Date",loca_geo1$Issue.Date,"<br/>",
                 "Vehicle Make",loca_geo1$Vehicle.Make,"<br/>",
                 "luxury",loca_geo1$luxury_car,"<br/>",
                 "count",loca_geo1$count,"<br/>")
(mpop3 <- m2 %>% addCircles(color= ~factpal(lux_repeat),  popup = content))
## Assuming "lon" and "lat" are longitude and latitude, respectively

(mclust <- m2 %>% addCircleMarkers(color=loca_geo1$luxury_car, weight = loca_geo1$count, popup = content,clusterOptions = markerClusterOptions()))
